\#\#\# User: Say I had;

```
 \begin{equation}
  \begin{cases}
     x = 0 \\
     y = 0 \\
     z = 0
    \end{cases}
    \qquad \text{and} \qquad
    \begin{cases}
     x = a \\
     y = a \\
     z = b
    \end{cases}
  \end{equation}

```

How could I insert a brace ( } ) in the second 'cases' to say x and y are equal to a. (i.e. } \= a ). 

I hope this is clear, if not I can sketch it out \- just let me know!

Thanks in advance!

 \-

\#\#\# Top Answer: You can open it with `\left.`, e.g.

```
\left. 
\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}
\right\rbrace = a

```

or,

```
\begin{equation}
\left\lbrace
\begin{array}{l}
\left. 
\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}
\right\rbrace = a\\
z = b
\end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}

```

