Question: Which of the following LaTeX code snippets correctly implements a system of equations with a right brace grouping x and y, indicating they are both equal to a, while z equals b?

A) \begin{equation}
     \begin{cases}
       x = a \\
       y = a \\
       z = b
     \end{cases}
   \end{equation}

B) \begin{equation}
     \begin{cases}
       x \\
       y \right\} = a \\
       z = b
     \end{cases}
   \end{equation}

C) \begin{equation}
     \left\lbrace
     \begin{array}{l}
       \left. 
       \begin{array}{c}
         x\\
         y
       \end{array}
       \right\rbrace = a\\
       z = b
     \end{array}
     \right.
   \end{equation}

D) \begin{equation}
     \begin{cases}
       x \\
       y \} = a \\
       z = b
     \end{cases}
   \end{equation}

Correct Answer: C

Explanation: Option C is the correct implementation using LaTeX to create a system of equations with a right brace grouping x and y, indicating they are both equal to a, while z equals b. This solution uses the \left. and \right\rbrace commands to create the proper bracing, and utilizes nested array environments to achieve the desired layout. Options A and D do not implement the grouping brace at all, while option B attempts to use the \right\} command incorrectly within the cases environment, which would result in a compilation error.

